Another crucial part of the American strategy was the "pacifi-ation" program, which was intended to push the Viet Cong from
"Hearts and Minds”
areas chosen by the United States and then "pacify” those regions by winning the "hearts and minds” of the people. But American ces were not adept at establishing the kind of rapport with Jvincial Vietnamese that the Viet Cong had created.
Gradually, the pacification program gave way to a heavy-Jded relocation strategy, through which American troops rooted villagers from their homes, sent them fleeing to ugee camps or into the cities (producing by 1967 more than Trillion refugees), and then destroyed the vacated villages i surrounding countryside. But the Viet Cong responded by iying to new sanctuaries elsewhere. The futility of the ited States’s effort was suggested by the statement of an ferican officer after flattening one such hamlet that it had -n "necessary to destroy [the village] in order to save it.”
As the war dragged on and victory remained elusive, some American officers and officials began to urge the president to expand the military efforts. The Johnson administration, however, resisted. Unwilling to abandon its commitment to South Vietnam for fear of destroying American "credibility” in the world, the government was also unwilling to expand the war too far, for fear of provoking direct intervention by the Chinese, the Soviets, or both. In the meantime, the president began to encounter additional obstacles and frustrations at home.
The War at Home
As late as the end of 1965, few Americans, and even fewer influential ones, had protested the American involvement in Vietnam. But as the war dragged on, political support for it began to erode. A series of "teach-ins” on university campuses, beginning at the University of Michigan in 1965, sparked a national debate over
